Arunachal Pradesh, o␀ers vast, unexplored terrains that
attract travellers seeking unique and o␀beat experiences.
Traditionally, indigenous communities engaged in trekking,
river navigation, and forest expeditions, but the formal
promotion of adventure tourism began in the late 20th century. A
major milestone was the establishment of the National Institute
of Mountaineering and Allied Sports (NIMAS) in Dirang in 2013,
which o␀ers specialised training in mountaineering, aero, and
aqua sports. Over the years, Arunachal Pradesh has gained
prominence as an adventure tourism destination, with key
activities including trekking and mountaineering in Tawang,
Mechukha Valley, Anini and Ziro etc, white-water rafting on the
Siang and Subansiri rivers etc, angling in Mahseer-rich rivers,
motorbiking and mountain biking across rugged terrains, and
aero sports like paragliding in Seppa, Mechukha and Dirang etc.
The state also o␀ers unique experiences in form of Salt well trails
in areas like Borduria, Nimok Pung (Tirap) etc which blend
heritage with adventure. The state has received accolades like
the ‘Best Emerging Destination’ award at the Lonely Planet
Travel Awards 2019 and will host signi␀cant adventure event -
3rd National Adventure Racing Championship in Mechukha.
M
However, despite its natural advantages, the state faces
S challenges such as limited accessibility, low tourist awareness,
I and an unorganised adventure tourism sector, preventing it
R
from fully leveraging its potential. Therefore, strengthening of
U
infrastructure, organisation of adventure circuits, and
O implementation of targeted marketing strategies are
essential. This policy aims to sustainably develop adventure
T
tourism within the state by ensuring ecological balance,
E economic bene␀ts for local communities, and adherence to
the highest safety standards.
R
